From wolfgang.viechtbauer at maastrichtuniversity.nl  Sun Nov 26 11:54:07 2017
From: wolfgang.viechtbauer at maastrichtuniversity.nl (Viechtbauer Wolfgang (SP))
Date: Sun, 26 Nov 2017 10:54:07 +0000
Subject: [R-meta] Meta-analysis of single group attitude scores
In-Reply-To: <65e92064-c9e7-d9db-6a05-c1be674e614e@dewey.myzen.co.uk>
References: <061D6819-DB56-464D-A27B-ED039332FB5B@yahoo.com>
 <65e92064-c9e7-d9db-6a05-c1be674e614e@dewey.myzen.co.uk>
Message-ID: <dc4818cc0bb64083be4946c2c7bd6524@UM-MAIL3216.unimaas.nl>

I agree that ideally one would want to use the raw mean (or raw mean minus neutral point) as the outcome measure. However, if studies differ in terms of the number of answering possibilities, then the raw values are not really comparable.

Two ideas:

1) Divide by the SD. So you then compute d = (mean - neutral point) / SD. Then the (large-sample) sampling variance can be estimated with:

1/n + d^2/(2*n)

2) Divide by the possible range (not the observed one!). So you then compute d = (mean - neutral point) / range. Then the sampling variance can be estimated with:

SD^2 / (n * range^2)

Best,
Wolfgang

